        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Singly Linked Lists — Overview

            A **singly linked list** is a linear data structure made of **nodes**.

            Each node contains:
            - **Data**
            - A **reference (pointer)** to the next node

            Unlike arrays:
            - Memory is **not contiguous**
            - Size can **grow or shrink dynamically**
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Node Structure

            Each node has two parts:

            - **Value** (data stored)
            - **Next** (reference to the next node)

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              Node["Node"] --> Data["Data"]
              Node --> Next["Next pointer"]
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Linked List Layout

            Nodes are connected in sequence.

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A["Data | Next"] --> B["Data | Next"] --> C["Data | Next"] --> Null["null"]
            /mermaid

            - The last node points to **null**
            - The first node is called the **head**
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Head of the List

            The **head** is the entry point to the list.

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              Head["Head"] --> A["Node 1"] --> B["Node 2"] --> C["Node 3"]
            /mermaid

            Without the head, the list is **lost**
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Traversing a Linked List

            To access elements:
            - Start at the **head**
            - Follow `next` references one by one

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              Head --> A --> B --> C --> D
            /mermaid

            Time complexity: **O(n)**
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Inserting at the Beginning

            Steps:
            1. Create a new node
            2. Point it to the current head
            3. Update head

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              New["New Node"] --> OldHead["Old Head"] --> A --> B
            /mermaid

            Fast operation: **O(1)**
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Inserting at the End

            Steps:
            1. Traverse to the last node
            2. Set its `next` to the new node

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A --> B --> C --> New["New Node"]
            /mermaid

            Time complexity: **O(n)**
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Deleting a Node

            To delete a node:
            - Update the `next` pointer of the previous node

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A --> B --> C --> D
              B -. bypass .-> D
            /mermaid

            No shifting required  
            Must manage pointers carefully
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Advantages & Disadvantages

            ## Advantages
            - Dynamic size
            - Efficient insertions/deletions
            - No memory reallocation

            ## Disadvantages
            - No random access
            - Extra memory for pointers
            - Slower traversal
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # When to Use Singly Linked Lists

            Use them when:
            - You need frequent insertions/deletions
            - Size is unknown or changing
            - Sequential access is enough

            Avoid them when:
            - You need fast indexing
            - Cache performance matters
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise — Singly Linked List

            In this exercise, you will **implement a singly linked list in Python** from scratch.

            A **singly linked list** is a linear data structure where:
            - Each element (node) stores **data**
            - Each node points to the **next node** in the list

            ## Structure Overview

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              Head --> Node1;
              Node1 --> Node2;
              Node2 --> Node3;
              Node3 --> Null;
            /mermaid

            ## Task

            Implement a singly linked list that supports the following operations:

            1. Create a `Node` class  
            2. Create a `SinglyLinkedList` class  
            3. Insert a value at the **end** of the list  
            4. Display all elements in the list  

            ## Steps to Follow

            1. Define a `Node` class with:
              - `data`
              - `next`
            2. Define a `SinglyLinkedList` class with:
              - a `head` pointer
            3. Implement an `append(value)` method
            4. Implement a `print_list()` method
            5. Test your implementation

            spoiler
            ```
            class Node:
                def __init__(self, data):
                    self.data = data
                    self.next = None


            class SinglyLinkedList:
                def __init__(self):
                    self.head = None

                def append(self, value):
                    new_node = Node(value)

                    if self.head is None:
                        self.head = new_node
                        return

                    current = self.head
                    while current.next:
                        current = current.next

                    current.next = new_node

                def print_list(self):
                    current = self.head
                    while current:
                        print(current.data, end=" -> ")
                        current = current.next
                    print("None")


            # Example usage
            lst = SinglyLinkedList()
            lst.append(10)
            lst.append(20)
            lst.append(30)

            lst.print_list()
            /spoiler
            </script>
